If your Java HashMap is experiencing high collision rates (e.g., 67%), it means too many keys are mapping to the same hash bucket, which degrades performance from O(1) to O(n) in worst cases.
Here’s how you can improve HashMap performance and reduce collisions:

1. Improve Your hashCode() Implementation
Problem: Poorly implemented hashCode() methods cause many keys to land in the same bucket.
Solution:
Ensure hashCode() distributes values uniformly.
Avoid using only part of the object's fields.
Use Objects.hash(...) or a well-tested algorithm.
Java

Copy code
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(field1, field2, field3);
}
2. Increase Initial Capacity
Problem: Too small an initial capacity causes frequent resizing and higher collision probability.
Solution:
Set initial capacity to (expectedSize / loadFactor) + 1.
Java

Copy code
Map<String, String> map = new HashMap<>(1024, 0.75f);
Tip: Keep load factor ≤ 0.75 for balance between memory and performance.
3. Use Immutable Keys
Problem: Mutable keys can change after insertion, breaking hash distribution.
Solution: Use String, UUID, or other immutable objects as keys.
4. Upgrade to Java 8+ for Tree Bins
Since Java 8, when a bucket exceeds 8 entries, it switches from a linked list to a balanced tree (O(log n) lookup).
Ensure you’re running Java 8+ to benefit from this.
5. Precompute Hashes for Expensive Keys
If computing hashCode() is expensive (e.g., large strings), store the hash in the object.

Java

Copy code
public class FastKey {
    private final String value;
    private final int hash;

    public FastKey(String value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.hash = value.hashCode();
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return hash;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        return o instanceof FastKey && value.equals(((FastKey) o).value);
    }
}
6. Consider Alternative Maps
If collisions remain high:

ConcurrentHashMap — better concurrency handling.
LinkedHashMap — predictable iteration order.
TObjectHashMap (Trove) or FastUtil — optimized for primitive keys.
✅ Example: Optimized HashMap Creation

Java

Copy code
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Objects;

public class OptimizedHashMapExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Expected 10,000 entries, load factor 0.75
        int expectedSize = 10_000;
        float loadFactor = 0.75f;
        int initialCapacity = (int) (expectedSize / loadFactor) + 1;

        Map<CustomKey, String> map = new HashMap<>(initialCapacity, loadFactor);

        // Insert sample data
        for (int i = 0; i < expectedSize; i++) {
            map.put(new CustomKey(i, "val" + i), "Data" + i);
        }

        System.out.println("Map size: " + map.size());
    }

    // Custom key with good hash distribution
    static class CustomKey {
        int id;
        String name;

        CustomKey(int id, String name) {
            this.id = id;
            this.name = name;
        }

        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            return Objects.hash(id, name);
        }

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object o) {
            if (this == o) return true;
            if (!(o instanceof CustomKey)) return false;
            CustomKey key = (CustomKey) o;
            return id == key.id && Objects.equals(name, key.name);
        }
    }
}
